"Scholl M.A., Giambelluca T.W., Gingerich S.B., Nullet M.A., Loope L.L.","Cloud water in windward and leeward mountain forests: The stable isotope signature of orographic cloud water",2007,"Water Resources Research","43","12", W12411,"","",,,10.1029/2007WR006011,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38549122407&partnerID=40&md5=717e559c9feb2e3b51e896e7f8d8ea03","Water Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Reston, VA, United States; Geography Department, University of Hawai'i at Manoa, Honolulu, HI, United States; Pacific Islands Water Science Center, U.S. Geological Survey, Honolulu, HI, United States; Biological Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Makawao, HI, United States; Geography Department, University of Hawai'i at Manoa, Honolulu, HI 96822, United States; Pacific Islands Water Science Center, U.S. Geological Survey, Honolulu, HI 96813, United States; Biological Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Makawao, HI 96768, United States; Water Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Reston, VA 20192-0002, United States","Scholl, M.A., Water Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Reston, VA, United States, Water Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Reston, VA 20192-0002, United States; Giambelluca, T.W., Geography Department, University of Hawai'i at Manoa, Honolulu, HI, United States, Geography Department, University of Hawai'i at Manoa, Honolulu, HI 96822, United States; Gingerich, S.B., Pacific Islands Water Science Center, U.S. Geological Survey, Honolulu, HI, United States, Pacific Islands Water Science Center, U.S. Geological Survey, Honolulu, HI 96813, United States; Nullet, M.A., Geography Department, University of Hawai'i at Manoa, Honolulu, HI, United States, Geography Department, University of Hawai'i at Manoa, Honolulu, HI 96822, United States; Loope, L.L., Biological Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Makawao, HI, United States, Biological Resources Discipline, U.S. Geological Survey, Makawao, HI 96768, United States","Cloud water can be a significant hydrologic input to mountain forests. Because it is a precipitation source that is vulnerable to climate change, it is important to quantify amounts of cloud water input at watershed and regional scales. During this study, cloud water and rain samples were collected monthly for 2 years at sites on windward and leeward East Maui. The difference in isotopic composition between volume-weighted average cloud water and rain samples was 1.4‰ δ18O and 12‰ δ2H for the windward site and 2.8‰ δ18O and 25‰ δ2H for the leeward site, with the cloud water samples enriched in 18O and 2H relative to the rain samples. A summary of previous literature shows that fog and/or cloud water is enriched in 18O and 2H compared to rain at many locations around the world; this study documents cloud water and rain isotopic composition resulting from weather patterns common to montane environments in the trade wind latitudes. An end-member isotopic composition for cloud water was identified for each site and was used in an isotopic mixing model to estimate the proportion of precipitation input from orographic clouds. Orographic cloud water input was 37% of the total precipitation at the windward site and 46% at the leeward site. This represents an estimate of water input to the forest that could be altered by changes in cloud base altitude resulting from global climate change or deforestation.",,"Climate change; Environmental engineering; Rain; Watersheds; Cloud water; Leeward mountain forests; Orographic cloud water; Windward; Forestry; Climate change; Environmental engineering; Forestry; Rain; Watersheds; climate change; cloud water; deforestation; isotopic composition; montane forest; precipitation (climatology); stable isotope; trade wind; Forestry; Rain; Water Sheds; Hawaii [United States]; Hawaiian Islands; Maui; North America; Pacific islands; Pacific Ocean; United States",,,,,,"Anderson, J.B., Baumgardner, R.E., Moh